06262nam a22009135i 9780812205763DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20112011pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013950247  a(OCoLC)979628022  a97808122057637 a10.9783/97808122057632doi  a(DE-B1597)449413  a(OCoLC)793012603  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aPOL0350102bisacsh04a320.94371 aDavid, Roman, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLustration and Transitional Justice :bPersonnel Systems in the Czech Republic, Hungary, and Poland /cRoman David. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2011] 4cÂ©2011  a1 online resource (328 p.) :b11 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPennsylvania Studies in Human Rights00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tList of Abbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tPart I. Personnel Systems and Transitional Justice -- t1. Personnel Systems and Their Classification -- t2. The Symbolic Meaning of Personnel Systems -- tPart II. Lustration Systems in Central Europe -- t3. Lustration Systems and Their Operation -- t4. The Origin of Lustration Systems -- t5. The Politics of Lustration Systems -- tPart III. Experimental Evidence -- t6. Political Effects: Trust in Government -- t7. Social Effects: Reconciliation and Collective Memory -- tConclusion -- tAppendix A. The Dilemmas of Personnel Systems -- tAppendix B. The Experimental Vignette -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow do transitional democracies deal with officials who have been tainted by complicity with prior governments? Should they be excluded or should they be incorporated into the new system? In Lustration and Transitional Justice, Roman David examines major institutional innovations that developed in Central Europe following the collapse of communist regimes. While the Czech Republic approved a lustration (vetting) law based on the traditional method of dismissals, Hungary and Poland devised alternative models that granted their tainted officials a second chance in exchange for truth. David classifies personnel systems as exclusive, inclusive, and reconciliatory; they are based on dismissal, exposure, and confession, respectively, and they represent three major classes of transitional justice.David argues that in addition to their immediate purposes, personnel systems carry symbolic meanings that help explain their origin and shape their effects. In their effort to purify public life, personnel systems send different ideological messages that affect trust in government and the social standing of former adversaries. Exclusive systems may establish trust at the expense of reconciliation, while inclusive and reconciliatory systems may promote both trust and reconciliation.In spite of its importance, the topic of inherited personnel has received only limited attention in research on transitional justice and democratization. Lustration and Transitional Justice is the first attempt to fill this gap. Combining insights from cultural sociology and political psychology with the analysis of original experiments, historical surveys, parliamentary debates, and interviews, the book shows how perceptions of tainted personnel affected the origin of lustration systems and how dismissal, exposure, and confession affected trust in government, reconciliation, and collective memory.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aDemocratizationxCzech Republic. 0aDemocratizationzHungary. 0aDemocratizationzPoland. 0aPolitical purgesxCzech Republic. 0aPolitical purgeszHungary. 0aPolitical purgeszPoland. 0aTransitional justicexCzech Republic. 0